To connect to a MySQL database from within node.js, you can use the [mysql](https://www.npmjs.com/package/mysql) npm package. You first need to install it in your project folder using the command:

```bash
npm install mysql
```
Once installed, you can import the package into your javascript file and start connecting to your MySQL database. Here's an example of how to connect to a MySQL database called "mydatabase":

```javascript
const mysql = require('mysql');

// Create a connection to the database
var con = mysql.createConnection({
 host: 'localhost',
 user: 'your_username',
 password: 'your_password',
 database: 'ydatabase'
});

// Connect to the database
con.connect(function(err) {
 if (err) throw err;
 console.log("Connected!");

 // Close the connection
 con.destroy();
});
```
Note that you will need to replace `"your_username"`, `"your_password"` and `'mydatabase'` with actual values appropriate for your own MySQL installation. Once you've established a connection, you can run queries against the database using the `query()` method. For example, suppose you want to retrieve all records from a table called "mytable". Your query might look like this:

```javascript
con.query('SELECT * FROM mytable', function (err, result, fields) {
 if (err) throw err;
 console.log(result);
});
```
Replace `mytable` with the actual name of the table you wish to query. The results of the query will be returned as an array of objects, where each object represents a single record in the table.

Alternatively, you can use an asynchronous programming style with promises instead of callbacks. Here's an equivalent example using promises:

```javascript
const mysql = require('mysql');

// Create a connection to the database
const conn = mysql.createConnection({
 host: 'localhost',
 user: 'your_username',
 password: 'your_password',
 database: 'ydatabase'
});

conn.connect()
 .then(() => {
 console.log('connected!');
 return conn.query('SELECT * FROM mytable')
 })
 .then((results) => {
 console.log(results);
 return conn.end();
 })"}
